liveBlogPostPrepared.plaintext: Talks are continuing between Woodside Energy and unions over planned strikes over pay and conditions on its offshore gas platforms. Woodside Energy's chief executive Meg O'Neill has told Reuters it is proceeding with respect in its talks with unions to avert industrial action at Australia's largest LNG facility, the North West Shelf. O'Neill told Reuters in an interview: "It takes two to tango. "We are proceeding with goodwill and with respect, and we are very focused on really understanding the key areas of concern. "But we also of course, have a duty to our shareholders to be able to run the business." The Offshore Alliance (OA), which represents LNG workers, said in a Facebook post that the cost for Woodside of not sorting out an agreement will be "infinitely greater" than any strikes. "It's time that Woodside's operations workforce got their fair share of the profits which they generate for the Woodside shareholders." "The OA member are primed and ready to go." Tomorrow is the deadline for Woodside to respond to the union's bargaining claims. Industrial action could start early next month. Industrial action would disrupt Australia's LNG exports, which represent about 10 per cent of global supply. Workers at Chevron's Wheatstone and Gorgon offshore platforms are also voting on industrial action over similar wage demands. Gas prices rose across Europe and Asia on the uncertainty.
liveBlogPostPrepared.title: LNG strike threat looms

liveBlogPostPrepared.plaintext: This is from Coles' full year presentation for shareholders today. The little chart in the middle says the group's total loss (which includes stock loss, waste, and markdown) increased by 20% year on year. It says a " key driver " of that elevated stock loss included " increased levels of organised crime and theft". It said supply chains disruptions also contributed to higher waste. It will be doing a number of things to reduce its loss revolving around security improvements, such as investments in AI skip scan and Smarter Gates, and more collaboration with police .
liveBlogPostPrepared.title: Coles gets hit by more theft and organised crime

liveBlogPostPrepared.plaintext: Alumina has swung from a profit of $US168 million to a loss of $US43 million ($67 million) for the first half of the 2023 financial year amid lower commodity prices and higher costs. Alumina invests in bauxite mining and alumina refining through Alcoa World Alumina and Chemicals, its joint venture with Alcoa Corporation. Alumina's chief executive Mike Ferraro says it has been a difficult first half and the company continues to face significant uncertainty due to ongoing delays with mining permits in Western Australia. "Alcoa is continuing to work with a range of WA government agencies on the approvals for it to operate our WA mines, which in turn supply bauxite to our WA alumina refineries." "We are operating in a complex regulatory environment where there is no certainty as to time frames or outcomes and the potential impacts on the business are unclear." The WA government is concerned about the impact of Alcoa's bauxite mining on drinking water supplies. Mr Ferraro says the alumina price had a strong start to the year before declining because of weak demand for aluminium outside China. "Prices have risen again in the last 3 weeks, reflecting the tight global balance for alumina and a recovery in aluminium production in China." Investors get no dividend payout
liveBlogPostPrepared.title: Alumina warns of uncertainty over WA mines
